<LI>Visited the Netherlands, Spain, France, Japan, China, Singapore, Taiwan, US, Thailand, Malaysia and almost all provinces of the Philippines.</LI>
 </UL>', '[Source: <A HREF=\"http://www.asison.ph/platform.html\">http://www.asison.ph/platform.html</A>]
<P>
<B>MGA KAPATID AT KADISTRITO
IKATLONG DISTRITO (3RD DISTRICT)
NG SIYUDAD QUEZON</B>
<P>
ANG INYONG LINGKOD AY NAIS KAYONG SILBIHAN BILANG KONGRESISTA NA AYON SA BAGONG POLITIKA. ANG MGA KATUNGALI KO AY MARAMING PANGAKO SA INYO. 
<UL>
<LI>PAKAY KO NA MAGING MABUTI AT MAALIWALAS ANG ATING KAPALIGIRAN. MAAARI NATING LINISIN ANG KOMUNIDAD SA BASURA SA PAGSASAAYOS NG \"WASTE MANAGEMENT\", IHIWALAY ANG BASANG BIODEGRADABLE SA RECYCLABLE. 
<LI>PONDOHAN NATIN ANG KOMPUTER EDUCATION PARA SA ATING KINABUKASAN. 
<LI>PONDOHAN ANG PAGTANIM NG PUNO. 
<LI>HIGPITAN ANG BATAS SA BARIL, LIMITAHAN ANG BATAS SA PERMIT TO CARRY FIREARMS, ALISIN ANG TAKOT SA ATING PALIGID, PALAKASIN ANG BARANGAY SA PAGSUPIL NG DROGA O GAMIT.
</UL>
<P>
ISA AKONG ABOGADO NA TUMULONG MAISULAT ANG 1987 NA SALIGANG BATAS. MAY KASANAYAN AKO SA PAGSASABATAS DAHIL MULA 1987 NAGTRABAHO AKO AT MAY MGA KLIYENTENG KONGRESISTA AT SENADOR. GALING SA AKIN NA MAILAGAY SA SALIGANG BATAS KOMISYON NG KARAPATANG PANTAO. 
<P>
NILABANAN KO ANG PAGMEMETRO NG TELEPONO (LABAN SA PHONE METERING). NAIPAGLABAN KO KAYO SA INYONG KARAPATAN. 
<P>
ABOGADO NG LABING-LIMANG TAON (15 YEARS) 
<P>
BROADKASTER SA RADIO VERITAS, RADIO BANDIDO, RADYO NG BAYAN AT DWBR-BUSINESS RADIO. 
<P>
MAKINIG SA 104.3FM-QUEZON CITY MULAS LUNES HANGGANG BIYERNES.
<P>
dado1955@nsclub.net<BR>
www.asison.ph<BR>
<P>
ANG INYONG LINGKOD ADRIAN \"DADO\" SISON.', '', '', '[Source: <A HREF=\"http://www.asison.ph/profile.html\">http://www.asison.ph/profile.htm</A>]
<P>
I was born in Manila 45 years ago inside a Hilman car within the Philippine General Hospital compound on March 2, 1956. Papa Sito Sison was driving and Mama Sony Sison was seated at the back seat. Mama Sony said I was in a hurry to be born. When Papa saw my head coming out he parked the car near the Philippine General Hospital gate and rushed inside the hospital to get a doctor. Papa found a nurse who came out of the hospital with a tray to carry all 9 pounds of me. She cut the umbilical cord it was about 4 o\'clock in the morning of March the second.Papa Sito and Mama Sony did their best to bring up 8 children with the guidance of our Lord, with humor, perseverance, and family bonding together with their neighbors and other members of the Christian Family Movement.
<P>
I was fortunate to receive a Jesuit education from Fr. Candelaria, Fr. Galdon, Fr. Ferriols, Fr. Samson, Fr. Hofilena, Fr. Malasmas, Fr. Joe Cruz, Fr. Balchand, Fr. Lahiff, Fr. Miguel Bernad, Ms. Loreto Franco, Mrs. Badua, Mrs. Rilloraza, Mrs. Oledan, Ms. Adsuara, Mr. Guanzon, Mr.Gonzales, Mr.& Mrs. Palma, Mrs. Gloria Macapagal Arroyo (now President of the Philippines), Fr. Macayan, Ms. Tendero. If I stayed longer than 16 years at the Ateneo de Manila I would have been a priest. Now I am a padre de pamilya, with two gregarious children, one teenager and the other wanting to be a teenager. 
<P>
My parenting style follows a democratic consultative and proactive approach. I do my best to make time for my wife Marge and our children, Ingrid Margaret and Paulo Luis. We listen to each other, we laugh and tell stories and we also pray together. I am a product of my environment, parental guidance, upbringing, and prayer.
<P>
I have been a broadcaster since 1975 in both televison and radio, in the following stations, Channel 4, 13, 5, Radio Veritas, Radio Bandido DZRJ, RADYO NG BAYAN, and BUSINESS RADIO 104.3 FM Manila <A HREF=\"www.nsclub.net/broadcasters\">www.nsclub.net/broadcasters</A>
<P>
Listen to DWBR 104.3 FM Manila Monday to Friday telefax (632)9246599 for your information and feedback on the radio show. e-mail : <A HREF=\"mailto:dwbr@nsclub.net\">dwbr@nsclub.net</A>
<P>
Since I did not become a priest, I enrolled in Law school at the University of the Philippines.
<P>
Our Law professors and teacher have taught us that we have to familiarize ourselves with the law, know what is the right procedure, understand the issues brought before us, put a premium to the arbritration and settlement of cases. Professor Tadiar taught us that you go to court not because you want to go to court but because you have to.
<P>
Professor Ed Garcia (A peace advocate and peace arbritator) asked me to assist him and other members of the 1986 Constitutional Commission .They drafted the 1987 Philippine Constitution. I assisted in talking to all the 48 Constitutional Commissioners to include the provisions on the abolition of the death penalty, the nuclear weapons provision and the Commission on Human Rights.
<P>
Assisted and advised several members of Congress in the drafting and the approval of legislation including the Congressional franchise for Televison and Cable Companies.
<P>
One of the organizers in 1987 of the House of Representatives Staff Association to give a voice for those occupying confidential positions and who are not regular employees of the House of Representatives.
<P>
I have successfully opposed the Mandatory Phone Metering by Telecommunications firms. <A HREF=\"www.pldt.com\">www.pldt.com</A>
<P>
Secured the authority for ICC Telecoms (now Bayantel) of the 300,000 land line licenses in Quezon City, Malabon, Valenzuela and the entire Bicol region and their international gateway license that allows international long distance communications.', '', 'asison@asison.ph', '', '(02)926-0155 ,(02)928-8901', '2', '20010521154617', '<B>Ideas on Legislation</B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>Strengthen the capacity of government to collect taxes as there are 17 million tax evaders out of the 32 million workforce, with 11 million unemployed. </LI>
<LI>Allow Community Radio to operate without Congressional Franchise</LI>
<LI>Amend the law Presidential degree 1986 that governs the Movie Television Review and Classification Board to address the issue of classification</LI>
<LI>Fund the reforestation of the community</LI>
<LI>Fund the education on WASTE MANAGEMENT</LI>
<LI>Fund Education on Gender Sensitivity</LI>
<LI>Fund the Livelihood Training and Community Upliftment</LI>
</UL>', '<B>Environment</B> <BR>
<UL>
<LI>fund the education on waste management</LI>
<LI>fund education on gender sensitivity</LI>
</UL>
<B>Taxation</B> <BR>
<UL>
<LI>encourage the 17 Million tax evaders to contribute to the country\'s growth.</LI>
<LI>make it mandatory for all Filipinos and Filipino residents to inform the Bureau of Internal Revenue of their yearly income and employment status.</LI>
<LI>assign the serial number appearing in the birth certificate as the tax file number or tax information number. For those not born in the Philippines nor have a Philippine birth certificate, the Bureau of Internal Revenue will recognize the SSS number assigned to the taxpayer.</LI> 
</UL>

<B>Education </B><BR>
<UL>
<LI>exempt private schools from income tax, and use the lost revenue for putting a limitation on the annual tuition fee increase</LI>
</UL>

<B>Livelihood</B> <BR>
<UL>
<LI>fund livelihood training and computer education for school dropouts and young unemployed persons</LI>
<LI>fund the reforestation of the community</LI>
<LI>fund the livelihood training and community upliftment</LI>
<LI>increase and update the database of human resources</LI>
</UL>

<B>Peace & Order</B> <BR>
<UL>
<LI>support gun control and dismantle private armies</LI>
</UL>

<B>Housing</B> <BR>
<UL>
<LI>strengthen the opportunities for affordable housing
</UL>
<B>Economics</B> <BR>
<UL>
<LI>bring down interest rates.</LI>
<LI>encourage counter- trade.</LI>
<LI>encourage Filipino entreprenuers to develop new technologies, to use technologies imported wholesale by the government for manufacturing, and increasing the local value added.</LI>
<LI>put safety-nets to address the effects of globalization.</LI>
<LI>remove the automatic allocation for debt-servicing</LI>
</UL>

<B>Energy</B> <BR>
<UL>
<LI>amend the power bill to include that private sector shoulder ninety percent of the debts of NAPOCOR.</LI>
<LI>securitize the remaining NAPOCOR debts.</LI>
</UL>
<B>Budget</B> <BR>
<UL>
<LI>use the voucher system for non-cash benefits given to government employees who can use the voucher for the expenditures in education, housing, and livelihood.</LI>
</UL>
<B>Cooperative</B>
<UL> 
<LI>make it mandatory for all agencies and government corporations to set up livelihood, credit, and other related cooperatives so that the family income may increase as this is an opportunity to provide employment to family and community members.</LI>
</UL>
<B>Justice</B> <BR>
<UL>
<LI>amend the rules of court to make it mandatory for all the parties to a case to use the modes of discovery.</LI>
<LI>exhaust administrative and arbitration remedies without prematurely resorting to court action.</LI>
<LI>strengthen the Commision on Human Rights.</LI>
</UL>
<B>Labor</B> <BR>
<UL>
<LI>review and amend the law on subcontracting</LI>
<LI>encourage all employers to provide that at least ten percent of the equity in the company be offered to each employees as stock options, using the SCANLON plan of profit sharing.</LI>
<LI>strengthen the labor management council, put a premium to arbitration of labor disputes.</LI>
<LI>give tax credits to employers who provide child friendly and day care centers for the nursing mothers.</LI>
<LI>fund gender sensitivity training.</LI>
<LI>provide unemployment insurance.</LI>
<LI>strengthen medical insurance</LI>
</UL>
<B>Elections</B> <BR>
<UL>
<LI>fund continuing voter education</LI>
<LI>provide government matching funds for candidates so that candidates who come from outside political dynasties can have a chance to be elected.</LI>
<LI>strengthen the party list.</LI>
<LI>pass the OVERSEAS workers absentee-voting law</LI>
</UL>
<B>Communications</B> <BR>
<UL>
<LI>fund the continuing computerization of all government institutions and amend republic act 7925 known as the Telecommunications Act.</LI>
<LI>allow Community Radio to operate without Congressional Franchise</LI>
<LI>amend Presidential decree 1986, the law that governs the Movie Television Review and Classification Board to address the lack of clear standards and the powers of the board over the new technologies and mediums for film showing. </LI>
</UL>', 'Dado', '', '1183', '0', 'N', '');
