</OL>', '', '', '[Source <A HREF=\"http://www.ruffybiazon.com/profile.htm\">http://www.ruffybiazon.com/profile.htm</A>]
<P>
The youngest of three children of Senator Rodolfo Biazon, Ruffy is not a newcomer in public service. 
<P>
From his birth in Cavite Naval Station to his stay in Fort Bonifacio from less than a year old to his full maturity twenty three years later, he has seen and even been a part of countless civic action missions conducted by his father’s unit in the AFP. With his father’s strong leadership influence, he led similar activities in school, where he was actively involved in organizations and the student council. In the latter years of then General Biazon’s colorful career, Ruffy spent hours discussing with his father the intricacies of politics and public service, driven by the same fervor that characterized his writings in the school newspaper as an editor. 
<P>
After high school, Ruffy dreamt of becoming a doctor with the noble intention of serving the people. As a pre-med course, he entered the University of Santo Tomas in and took up Medical Technology as a pre-med course. But fate had a different story for him. After his four years in UST, his life took a turn towards a different direction, although with the same objective---serving the people. 
<P>
When he got out of college in 1991, he was appointed by then President Corazon Aquino to be a member of the Board of Directors of the Videogram Regulatory Board (VRB) representing the youth. Acting in a similar function as the MTRCB (Movie and Television Ratings and Classification Board), the VRB rates and classifies videogram materials, which are essentially those in video shops and video clubs. 
<P>
When his father, then newly retired Chief of Staff of the AFP, first ran for senator  in 1992, he was appointed as Operations Director of the campaign organization. Although the campaign organization was not well funded and staffed by newcomers in politics, Ruffy was able draw up and implement and effective operations plan. As fate would have it, his father won a seat in the Senate. Immediately after that victory, Ruffy asked to organize the office due to his organizing skills, with the condition that he will continue on the medical school. But the exposure to being able to directly bring public service and the complexity of politics lured him to stay. 
<P>
As Chief of Staff of the Office of Senator Biazon, he practically was the right hand man of the senator. Aside from managing the daily administration of the office, he was also tasked to formulate projects for the Office’s public service programs. He was also the Chief Political Officer, to which he was delegated the task of liaising with other politicians, government agencies and private institutions. More importantly, he supervised the Legislative Staff, the group in the office that dealt with the primary task of a Senator---lawmaking. As such, he was responsible in leading the research and drafting of several important bills of the senator at that time such as the bill mandating the infusion of computer literacy subjects in all public elementary and high schools. 
<P>
In the 1995 elections, Ruffy was designated as Campaign Manager of Senator Biazon for his re-election bid. Although the campaign was effectively and efficiently run, the lack of campaign funds to match those spent by traditional moneyed politicians during the counting allowed Senator Biazon to be victimized by Dagdag-Bawas operators. For Ruffy, it opened an opportunity for him to go to Medical School. 
<P>
But as fate would have it, he was recruited by then newly-elected Senator Sergio Osmeña III to be his Chief Legislative Officer, tasked with heading the group which performed the lawmaking functions of the office. Ruffy used his previous experience to draw up an efficient team which became responsible in supporting Senator Osmeña in his legislative work. Landmark bills such as the Retail Trade Act and Public Services Act marked the output of the team. The investigation into the questionable Marconi Radar Contract was one of the important works of the team led by Ruffy which resulted into the cancellation of the contract. Another was the investigation into the series of sea tragedies which revealed the anomalies being done in the maritime agencies in the government. 
<P>
To prepare for Senator Biazon’s bid to return to the Senate in 1998, Ruffy resigned from the Office of Senator Osmeña in 1997 and prepared the groundwork for the campaign. Drawing on his organizing skills, political acumen and previous experience, Ruffy as Campaign Manager successfully steered the campaign of Senator Biazon to victory. 
<P>
Once again, Ruffy occupies the position of Chief of Staff of a senator’s office. More seasoned and mature this time around, he has taken on his role with much gusto. Once again, he has led the legislative staff of Senator Biazon to perform beyond the senator’s expectations. Effective management of human and material resources has brought about an effective and efficient office, with outputs surpassing those of other senators. 
<P>
In July of 2000, the Philippines played host to the 3rd Conference of the Global Parliamentarians on Habitat, an organization of parliamentarians and legislators from all over the world. Ruffy’s experience and skill in logistics management was once more tapped when he was appointed Director for Administration and Logistics of the conference secretariat. Without a hitch, the conference was conducted successfully, with more than 300 representatives from more than a hundred countries attending.  
<P>
But the most important contribution of Ruffy to the senator’s office are the innovations and public service programs he has initiated. Being an avid information technology hobbyist (he is proficient in webpage design, computer graphics and multimedia applications), he has introduced computerization into the senator’s office making it one of the best equipped offices in the senate. He also provides the senator with insight on information technology, enabling the Senator to formulate proposals in the field of computerization. 
<P>
Being a resident of Muntinlupa, Ruffy formulated Compu.T.E.R.S. Project (Computer Training for Educators and Resources for Students Project) in Muntinlupa schools. Upon the recommendation of Ruffy, an initial amount of Three Million Pesos from Senator Biazon’s CDF was released for the purchase of computers for Muntinlupa National High School and Pedro E. Diaz High School and software training for the teachers. A second allocation amounting to Ten Million Pesos was released for the Compu.T.E.R.S. Project which would provide computers to all the four public high schools and fifteen public elementary schools plus software training for 740 public school teachers. Ruffy has also implemented an Internet Use Seminar for the students and teachers of Pedro Diaz High School, in preparation for the next project, the Internet Connection Project for high schools. 
<P>
Having gone around the country since 1992 delivering services in behalf of the senator, Ruffy has chosen to concentrate on the City of Muntinlupa. With his active participation in the legislative process since 1992, is knowledgeable about a wide range of issues, particularly those about information technology, education, public order and security, national defense, urban development and housing. 
<P>
His exposure in the Committee on Housing, Urban Planning and Resettlement which Senator Biazon chairs has given rise to his concern for those in the urban poor sector, particularly in Muntinlupa. He has formed MRB, Muntinlupa para sa Reproma at Bayanihan, a group that immerses itself in the urban poor communities of Muntinlupa and other sectors like the youth and the women, to get first hand information about the prevailing issues in those sectors to come up with legislative proposals that meet their needs. In addition, MRB has conducted numerous regular public service projects such as medical missions, water supply and support to activities of youth and community organizations. 
<P>
He has also initiated the “I Care for Day Care Project” of the Office of Senator Biazon, which benefits all 46 day care centers under the supervision of Muntinlupa Social Welfare Department. 
<P>
In his personal capacity, he is a director in ZONTAR Manpower Agency and Black Stallion Security Agency, both of which he is one of the incorporators.', '', 'ruffy@ruffybiazon.com', '8093132', '0919-2015658', '0', '20010418130436', '', '', 'Ruffy', '', '0', '0', 'N', '');
