</PRE>', '', 'Legislative Agenda of Boy Seseng<BR>
<P>
I. Enactment of Laws
<P>
1. Livelihood and Job Creation <BR>
<P>
“Shoe Export Processing Zone Law” – law to declare Marikina City as an export processing zone for the Shoe industry to encourage the return and establishment of shoe factories in Marikina where they can import, free from taxes, raw materials and equipment for their production, thereby substantially reducing the cost of production.
<P>
“Marikina Shoebank” – law creating a shoe bank that shall service the financial needs of shoe manufacturers, small and big entrepreneurs, as well as the shoe laborers.
<P>
2. Education <BR>
<P>
“Public School Computerization Law” – law mandating Information Technology as part of the curriculum in all public high schools, providing computers on all public schools and allocating the budgetary requirements thereof, with the aim that all public high school graduates, even without college education, shall have basic computer skills. 
<P>
3. Health <BR>
<P>
“Comprehensive Health Insurance Law” – law requiring Cities to set aside portion of its city budget in providing a health care insurance program for its residents, with the aim of extending a subsidized insurance premium payment for a heallth/medicare program to all residents of the City.
<P>
4. Housing <BR>
<P>
“Housing Program Devolution Law” – a law that will devolve or delegate to Cities the mass housing program of the National Government, empowering Cities to enter into mass housing projects to be financed by the National Government.
<P>
5. Crime Prevention <BR>
<P>
“Extended Illegal Drugs Law” – law amending existing law on illegal drugs by increasing the coverage and penalty for illegal possession.
<P>
6. Tax Alleviation <BR>
<P>
“Estate/Inheritance Exemption Law” – law to exempt estates or properties left by the deceased worth One Million Pesos (P1,000,000) and below from payment of Estate/Inheritance taxes.
“Capital Gains Tax Exemption Law” – law providing the exemption from payment of Capital Gains Tax of the sale or transfer of property valued at Five Hundred Thousand Pesos (P500,000.00) or below as well as providing for a one-time tax exemption from Capital Gains Tax of a sale of a property of a senior citizen.
<P>
II. Local Concerns
<P>
1. Creation of Marikina Foreign Trade Mission <BR>
<P>
Creation of core group that will administer the Foreign Trade Mission for the city. Their main task is to promote Marikina Products specifically the shoe making industry to global market and encourage foreign investors to invest in Marikina.
<P>
This will strengthen and flourish the Marikina business sector, and will provide employment to the many Marikenos.  
<P>
2. Training Center For the Youth <BR>
<P>
Empowering the youth through an information technology by establishing a Training Center with competent instructors, conducive and complete learning facilities.
<P>
This will give chance to less fortunate families whose desire for their child is to acquire value education. The training center will provide scholarships to qualified youth of the city, giving them the opportunity to learn today’s demand for information technology, so that they can contriute more, not only to the city but to the country as a whole.
<P>
3. Micro-Finance Program <BR>
<P>
Develop a Lending Institute that will provide immediate cash loan for small-scale businesses with minimal interest and easy payment scheme.
<P>
4. Health Income Benefit For Senior Citizen <BR>
<P>
Provide Senior Citizen ages 45-65 years old the benefit of having FREE medical assistance and P500.00 cash benefit per day of necessary confinement for every illness for 365 days.
<P>
5. Personal Accisent Insurance For Pedicab, Tricycle & Jeepney Drivers <BR>
<P>
FREE accident insurance will be made available for pedicab, tricycle and jeepney drivers.
<P>
This will assure them of P10,000 cash benefit in case of accidental death, and P5,000 up to P10,000 for accidental dismemberment.
<P>
6. Drug Prevention Program <BR>
<P>
Develop drug prevention programs for the entire city. Concentrating on massive campaigns to scrap drug dependencies and avoidance. Enhancing the youth’s participation in various community projects and programs that will discourage them in using or even getting involved with illegal drugs.', '<PRE>
