<UL>
<UL>
<LI>In 2000, with half the development funds unreleased, the sector posted 
another strong year – a 3.4 per cent growth rate, with all sectors declared as 
winners for a balanced growth. </LI></UL></UL>
<UL>
<UL>
<LI>Angara also fought for fair trading rules in a free trade environment. In 
several international meetings on free trade, Angara urged developed economies 
to stop pampering their farm producers with illegal subsidies and put an end to 
tariff distortions that had scarred the noble aims of free trade. 
</LI></UL></UL>
<UL>
<UL>
<LI>He established scholarships and invested heavily on training – his legendary 
love for investing on people. </LI></UL></UL>
<UL>
<UL>
<LI>He re-engineered production programs and lifted research and development – 
with focus on frontier work – from the margin. 
<LI>Modern agriculture got a new but human face under Angara. </LI></UL></UL>', '', '', '', '[Source: <A HREF=\"http://www.angara.net/profile.htm\">http://www.angara.net/profile.htm</A>]<BR><BR>
<P align=justify>Educator, legislator, banker, lawyer, art patron and farmer and 
former Executive Secretary and Secretary of Agriculture. Edgardo J. Angara is 
indeed a man of many facets and pursuits. In all of these preoccupations, Angara 
has stood out and made his mark.</P>
<P align=justify>Born to middle-class parents in Baler, Aurora, Angara scaled up 
the ladder of corporate law, the academe of politics to emerge as one of the 
country’s top public leaders and intellectuals.</P>
<P align=justify>A product of the University of the Philippines (Bachelor of 
Laws, 1958), and the University of Michigan (Master of Laws, 1964), he founded 
in the early seventies what eventually became one of the country’s most 
prestigious law firms – the Angara, Concepcion, Cruz, Regala and Abello (ACCRA) 
Law Offices.</P>
<P align=justify>He gained prominence during his stint as the Presidentof the 
University of the Philippines from 1981 to 1987. During the turbulent years of 
his stewardship at UP, he defended not only the State University’s tradition of 
dissent but also significantly improved its financial and human resources, Under 
his term, UP established stronger links with the business community and alumni 
organizations, both locally and abroad.</P>
<P align=justify>His achievements as UP President and active involvement in the 
Citizens watchdog group NAMFREL during the 1986 \"snap elections\" pushed him to 
national prominence and mainstream politics. He placed 5<SUP>th</SUP> in the 
senatorial election in 1987, the first free election after martial law.</P>
<P align=justify>He was named \"No. 1 Senator\" of the 8<SUP>th</SUP> Congress by 
the UP Institute of Strategic Development Studies. He was 3<SUP>rd</SUP> in the 
1992 senatorial elections and from 1993 to 1995, he served as Senate 
President.</P>
<P align=justify>During Angara’s term as Senate President, the chamber was an 
activist, reformist institution. He pushed hard for the passage of over 100 laws 
that turned around the economy and laid down the environment for economic 
dynamism and growth. A new Philippine Central Bank was created, the banking 
system was liberalized, and infrastructure build up boosted the economy with the 
massive entry of foreign investments.</P>
<P align=justify>Also during his term as Senate President, Angara’s reformist 
bent was the sheer force that cut through the legislative gridlock to pass 
landmark legislation.</P>
<P align=justify>As a legislator, he was identified with landmark laws in 
education, health, the arts , culture, and agriculture. He had a special concern 
for the underclass, He was the principal author of the law granting free high 
school education to all Filipinos. He authored the Magna Carta for Public Health 
Workers. He also headed the congressional commission that turned out a landmark 
comprehensive report on Philippine education. The report was the basis for the 
restructuring of the education department and the on-going major reforms in the 
educational system.</P>
<P align=justify>Two laws sponsored by Angara created the Commission on Higher 
Education and Technical Education and Skills Development Authority and this 
enabled the education department to focus on its main concern – basic 
education.</P>
<P align=justify>He also sponsored the passage of the Agriculture, Fisheries and 
Modernization Act which mandates the allocation of 120 billion pesos for the 
modernization of the agricultural sector for a period of seven years.</P>
<P align=justify>For those in the margin, Angara authored the Senior Citizens 
Act and the Breast Feeding Act. He co-authored the landmark Generics Drug Act 
and authored the law that provided a National Insurance Program for Filipinos 
(PhilHealth).</P>
<P align=justify>A committed patron of the arts, he was the principal sponsor of 
a law that created the new National Museum. A law he sponsored created the 
National Commission on Culture and the Arts. The law on National Living 
Treasures bestows great honor on traditional and folk artists.</P>
<P align=justify>As Secretary of the Department of Agriculture (DA), Angara had 
been the chief steward in increasing production, expanding markets, correcting 
policy biases and promoting the cause of agriculture and fisheries.</P>
<P align=justify>Frontier research work in agriculture research and development 
had been another hallmark of Angara’s leadership at the DA. The great strides 
recently achieved by the sector had been largely attributed to his 
leadership.</P>
<P align=justify>Angara also became a solid voice in the fight for fair trading 
rules in global trade. He coined the phrase \"fair trade in a free trade context\" 
to dramatize the resolve of the developing countries to end the protectionist 
and unfair trade policies of developed countries. His bargaining with Australia 
over the entry of world-class fruits to that country’s market had been widely 
hailed in the country’s farming and trade circles.</P>
<P align=justify>From a negative 6.6 percent performance in 1998, the 
agriculture sector had registered solid growths during the one year and a half 
Angara was secretary. The growth rate for the year 2000 was 3 percent. Palay 
production, according to field reports, was expected at 12.5 million metric 
tons, a historic record. The drive to gain self-sufficiency in rice, an elusive 
goal, is about to become a reality, thanks to the production programs and 
support services initiated under his stewardship of the agriculture 
department.</P>
<P align=justify>In 1999, the sector posted a growth rate of 6.7 percent.</P>
<P align=justify>The sector is expected to register a decent growth rate for the 
current year.</P>
<P align=justify>Having taken his oath on January 6, 2001 as Executive Secretary 
he was responsible for the peaceful transition of the presidency from Estrada to 
Arroyo, and the peaceful transition of power would not have been possible were 
it not for Angara and his unwavering commitment to serve his country until the 
very end.</P>
<P align=justify>Before joining the Estrada cabinet on May 25, 1999, he served 
as Chairman of the Philippine National Bank.</P>
<P align=justify>He is married to Gloria Manalang, who was former chair of the 
Cultural Center of the Philippines. They have for children.</P>', 'Baler, Aurora', '', '', '', '2', '20010623104303', '', '', 'Ed', '', '10746843', '2', '8121808', 'Y', '618407', '367943', '1386246', '1986612', '467587', '733032', '494799', '413589', '340020', '382985', '804105', '352112', '188064', '83672', '1888176', '239257', '237', '');
INSERT INTO candsenators VALUES ( '3', 'Arroyo', 'Joker', 'P', '233', 'candsenator - joker arroyo.jpg', '1927-01-02', '', '<B>EDUCATION</B><BR>
Law, A.B., University of the Philippines<BR>
Pre-Law, Ateneo de Manila<BR>
<BR>
<B>During the Marcos Dictatorship - 1972-1986</B><BR>
Human Rights Lawyer, Freedom Fighter<BR>
<UL>
<LI>First lawyer to challenge before the Supreme Court the constitutionality of Proclamation 1081 imposing martial law.
<LI>Thereafter, he questioned before the Supreme Court along with others:
	<OL>
   <LI>The ratification of the Marcos-dictated 1973 constitution;
   <LI>Amendment Six that empowered President Marcos to exercise law-making powers alongside the Batasan Pambansa;
   <LI>The power of military tribunals to try civilians.
	</OL>
<LI>Participated before military commissions in the defense of Ninoy Aquino, Eugenio Lopez, Jr., Jose Maria Sison, Commander Dante, Jovito Salonga, Eva Kalaw and many others.
<LI>Handled more human rights cases than any other lawyer, from 1972-1986.
<LI>Incarcerated, thrown into a bartolina and held incommunicado and in solitary in a military stockade.
<LI>Gassed, injured and hospitalized during protest rallies.
<LI>Counsel of Cory Aquino in the snap elections.
<LI>Co-founded FLAG and MABINI.
<LI>His professional affiliations include the American Bar Association, the International Bar Association (London), and the Union Internationale de Advocats (Paris).
</UL>
<BR>
<B>After EDSA</B><BR>
Executive Secretary<BR>
<UL>
<LI>First Appointee of Cory Aquino<BR>
Chairman of the Philippine National Bank<BR>
<LI>1986-1990<BR>
Philippine Director to the Asian Development Bank<BR>
<LI>1986-1990<BR>
Founding Chairman, First Philippine Fund, New York<BR>
</UL>
<P>
The Senate extended him a rare commendation in Senate Resolution No. 100 “Commending Joker P. Arroyo for His Invaluable Services to the Filipino People”
<P>
The 104-year old Philippine Bar Association awarded him its “Most Distinguished Award for Justice” as a “man beholden to no one except to his country.”
<BR><BR>
<B>In Congress - 1992, 1995 and 1998</B><BR>
Representative, 1st District of Makati obtaining 80% of the votes cast in the elections<BR>
<UL>
<LI>100% attendance record in the House of Representatives since his election; remained the only independent.
<LI>He has never travelled abroad on government money.
<LI>His Statement of Assets and Liabilities has remained the same from the time he entered public service in 1986 up to the present.
<LI>Consistently voted every year by media as “Outstanding Congressman of the Year.”
<LI>Prosecutor in the Impeachment Case against Joseph Ejercito Estrada.
</UL>', '', '', '', '', 'Naga City', '', '', '', '2', '20010628193913', '', '', 'Joker', '', '11163801', '1', '8495848', 'Y', '788662', '316394', '1372714', '1507370', '891065', '1087085', '1103862', '443372', '312630', '312387', '496864', '161852', '220529', '178309', '1698963', '271567', '176', '');
