INSERT INTO candsenators VALUES ( '9', 'Drilon', 'Franklin', 'M', '465', 'candsenator - franklin drilon.jpg', '1945-11-28', '', '', '', '', '', '[Source: <A HREF=\"http://www.sendrilon.org.ph/biography.html\">http://www.sendrilon.org.ph/biography.html</A>]<BR><BR>
<P align=left><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>BORN on 
November 28, 1945 in Iloilo City, Franklin M. Drilon is the eldest of four 
children of Primitiva Drilon and the late Cesar M. Drilon, Sr. A product of the 
public schools, he finished his elementary education in Baluarte Elementary 
School in Molo, Iloilo City in 1957; high school in UP Iloilo College in 1961, 
and received Bachelor of Arts and Bachelor of Laws degrees from the University 
of the Philippines (UP) in 1965 and 1969, respectively. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>In UP, he did not 
only excel in academics; he was a student leader. He was elected University 
Councilor of the Student Council; served as associate editor of the Philippine 
Collegian, the country’s premier campus paper; member of the Editorial Board of 
the prestigious Philippine Law Journal; member of the Order of the Purple 
Feather, the honor society of the U.P. College of Law; and member of the Sigma 
Rho Fraternity.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>A brilliant legal 
mind, he placed third in the 1969 Bar Exams. After passing the Bar Examinations, 
he joined the Sycip, Salazar, Luna, Manalo &amp; Feliciano Law Offices. In 1974, 
he started his career with the Angara, Abello, Concepcion, Regala &amp; Cruz 
(ACCRA) Law Offices as senior associate, rose from the ranks to become a 
partner, co-managing partner and finally as managing partner and head of the 
said law firm on August 11, 1986. He resigned in September 1986 leaving the 
lucrative practice of law to join the government of President Aquino as Deputy 
Minister of Labor.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>Drilon served as 
Secretary of Labor from January 1987 to January 1990; Secretary of Justice (DOJ) 
from January 1990 to July 1991; Executive Secretary from July 1991 to June 1992; 
again, Secretary of DOJ from July 1992 to February 1995. He had served in the 
Cabinet of two Presidents--Corazon Aquino and Fidel V. Ramos. He served in the 
governing boards and councils of various government corporations and 
institutions, such as being Chairman of the Philippine National Bank; member of 
the board of Directors of Land Bank and Philippine Airlines; Chairman of the 
Presidential Committee on Human Rights and the Cabinet Cluster “E” on Political 
and Security matters; Chairman of the Philippine Overseas Employment Agency and 
Overseas Worker Welfare Administration; Vice-Chairman, Judicial and Bar 
Council.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>During the 1995 
Senatorial campaign, Drilon ran on the slogan “Kontra sa Krimen, Justice Agad”, 
a reminder of how, as Justice Secretary, he spearheaded the crusade to bring to 
the bar of justice the seemingly high and mighty -- the likes of Calauan, Laguna 
Mayor Antonio Sanchez, Claudio Teehankee, Jr., and Rolito Go. He promised the 
people that, when elected, he will introduce legislation to improve the justice 
system. The people believed in his cause, and elected him Senator, placing 4th. 
</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>He kept his 
promise. Thus, immediately after his election as Senator, Drilon filed various 
measures designed to speed up the trial of cases in the courts, strengthen the 
free legal services to the poor, and declog court dockets by prescribing 
arbitration rules and procedures on commercial disputes. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>A few months after 
the resumption of the 10th Congress, Senator Drilon was immediately recognized 
as one of the foremost legal minds in the Senate when it comes to deliberations 
in committee hearings and on the Senate Floor. For his outstanding performance 
in his first year in the Senate, Drilon was voted by the Senate press corps as 
the “Most Promising” among the neophyte Senators. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>He did not only 
concentrate on the country’s justice system. He also drafted and filed bills for 
the benefit of the working class; on banking; on housing; on electoral reforms, 
to name a few. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>In the 10th 
Congress (1995-1998), Senator Drilon was chairman of Senate Committees on 
Accountability of Public Officers and Investigations (Blue Ribbon); Banks, 
Financial Institutions and Currencies; Finance Committee Sub-Committee VI and 
Agricultural Commission (Agricom) Sub-Committee on Productions and Support 
Services. He was vice-chairman of Senate Committee on Justice and Human Rights 
and a member of 20 other Senate committees. He was also Member of the powerful 
Commission on Appointments. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>In the present 11th 
Congress, Drilon serves as the Majority Floor Leader, Chairman of the Committee 
on Rules and Committee on Accounts, and ex-officio member of all Senate standing 
committees. He continues to serve as member of the Commission on Appointments. 
</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>In professional and 
civic organizations, Drilon was a Bar Examiner on Labor and Social Legislation 
in 1979 and 1984; a member of the Makati Rotary Club; past Chapter president of 
the Integrated Bar of the Philippines (IBP); past governor of the Employers 
Confederation of the Philippines (ECOP) and past vice-president of the Personnel 
Management Association of the Philippines (PMAP).</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>A former member of 
the National Unification Commission (NUC), Senator Drilon now sits as adviser to 
the government panel in the Government of the Republic of the 
Philippines-National Democratic Front/Communist Party of the Philippines/New 
People’s Army (GRP-NDF/CPP/NPA) peace talks.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>Drilon is a 
recipient of the much coveted award of the Philippine Legion of Honor and a 
Presidential citation for outstanding public service. He was named the Most 
Outstanding UP Alumnus in government service for 1994 by the UP Law Alumni 
Association. He was conferred the degree of Doctor of Laws, honoris causa, by 
the Central Philippine University.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>He is also a sports 
enthusiast. He jogs a lot to stay physically fit and ready for any challenge 
that he may have to take in some future time. When not reading books, mainly 
non-fiction, or listening to his favorite songs, he tends to the orchid gardens 
his loving wife left behind. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>Drilon was married 
to the late Atty. Violeta Calvo Drilon, with whom he had two children, Eliza and 
Patrick. A widower no more, he recently took a bride, Mila Serrano Genuino, a 
sweet and talented lass from Manila and Bicol.</FONT></P>', 'Molo, Iloilo City', '', '', '', '2', '20010623104303', '', '', 'Frank', '', '11223020', '1', '8518543', 'Y', '784594', '353114', '1315352', '1519429', '674370', '1409868', '1100112', '434334', '289459', '329793', '542843', '179988', '216969', '156828', '1640111', '275654', '202', '');
INSERT INTO candsenators VALUES ( '10', 'Enrile', 'Juan', 'P', '243', 'candsenator - enrile.jpg', '1924-02-14', '', '[Source: <A HREF=\"http://www.juanponceenrile.com/legislative-achievements.html\">http://www.juanponceenrile.com/legislative-achievements.html</A>]<BR><BR>
<B>JPE - A MAN OF INTEGRITY, COPETENCE AND HONOR</B> <BR><BR>With a political 
career spanning over three decades, Senator Juan Ponce Enrile is hailed as the 
most veteran and experienced among all the senatorial candidates in the coming 
election. This tax expert from Harvard Law School was first recruited in 1966 to 
serve the government as Undersecretary of the Department of Finance. 
Concurrently, he held the chairmanship of the Monetary Board and acted as the 
Insurance Commissioner and Commissioner of Customs. He went on to occupy more 
key positions in the government including the Department of Justice and 
Department of National Defense. His seventeen-year stint in the Defense 
Department was highlighted by his withdrawal of support for the twenty-year old 
government of President Ferdinand Marcos, which led to the revolt that triggered 
the historical People Power or EDSA Revolution. <BR><BR>
<HR width=\"100%\" SIZE=1>
<B>FRUITFUL SENATORIAL STINT</B> 
<HR width=\"100%\" SIZE=1>
Excellence undoubtedly marked his stay in the government while serving in 
various capacities. In 1987, he was the lone opposition Senator and thus 
provided a constructive minority by being an effective fiscalizer to the new 
Aquino government. In 1992, he won a seat in the House of Representatives by a 
landslide representing the First District of Cagayan, his home province. He went 
back to the Senate in 1995 and chaired two powerful committees namely, 
Government Corporations and Public Enterprises, and Ways and Means. <BR><BR>As 
Chairman of the Senate Committee on Ways and Means, he spearheaded the enactment 
of laws, which promote economic reforms by generating more income for the 
government. In crafting these legislative measures, he stressed the importance 
of a simplified tax system so as not to make taxation more burdensome and 
onerous for the taxpaying public as well as promote efficiency in revenue 
collection. To achieve this, he authored the following bills: 
<UL>
<LI><B>Republic Act 8424 - Comprehensive Tax Reform Program</B> <BR><BR>SALIENT 
FEATURES: 
<OL>
<LI>Exemption from tax of all income earned abroad by an Overseas Filipino 
Worker thus enabling the OFWs to save a substantial amount of their hard-earned 
income for their families. 
<LI>Exemption from capital gains tax of proceeds realized from the sale of one\'s 
family home provided that said proceeds will utilized to acquire another 
residential home. 
<LI>Substantial increase in personal exemption granted to individual taxpayers 
earning compensation income. 
<LI>Substantial increase in personal allowances granted to dependents of 
individual taxpayers. </LI></OL><BR>
<LI><B>SBN 2048 - An Act Exempting from Tax Certain Allowances and Benefits 
Granted to Members of the Armed Forces of the Philippines (AFP)</B><BR><BR>
<LI><B>SBN 2082 - An Act Exempting from Tax All Allowances and Benefits Granted 
to Public School Teachers</B><BR><BR>
<LI><B>RA 8751 - An Act Providing Rules for Countervailing Duties on the 
Importation of Subsidized Products.</B> It has for its purpose the protection of 
local industries, which will be adversely affected by a massive importation of 
subsidized products.<BR><BR>
<LI><B>RA 8752 - An Act Providing the Rules for the Imposition of Anti-Dumping 
Duty.</B> Its purpose is to shield the local producers from the harsh effects of 
importation of cheap dumped goods.<BR><BR>
<LI><B>RA 8800 - An Act Providing Safeguards for Agricultural Products whose 
Quantitative Restrictions had been Replaced with Ordinary Customs Duties.</B> 
This bill seeks to protect the agricultural sector from the flooding of low 
quality products imported from abroad.<BR><BR>
<LI><B>SBN 2232 - An Act Elevating the Rank of the Court of Tax Appeals (CTA) to 
the level of a Collegiate Court with Special Jurisdiction.</B> This bill will 
enlarge the jurisdiction of the CTA and its organizational structure to promote 
efficient tax collection.<BR><BR>
<LI><B>SBN 2208 - An Act Providing Optimum Performance in Revenue Collection 
through Lateral Attrition.</B> This bill grants special incentives and rewards 
for exemplary service in revenue-generating agencies of the government. It 
likewise imposes a penalty to employees of said agencies who fail to meet the 
collection quota.<BR><BR></LI></UL>As Chairman of the Senate Committee on 
Government Corporations and Public Enterprises, he has exposed certain 
irregularities in the government, which led to a string of graft charges against 
the culprit involved. Incisive legislative inquiries and well-documented public 
hearings were concluded in order to shed light on the following controversial 
issues: PEA-Amari Land Scam, Tax Credit Scam in the DOF and Purchase of Luxury 
Vehicles by DECS Officials. <BR><BR>
<HR width=\"100%\" SIZE=1>
<B>AS A SENATOR-JUDGE</B> 
<HR width=\"100%\" SIZE=1>
His fruitful stint in the Senate was marked with a genuine desire to serve the 
public. This was again proven during the much-publicized impeachment trial of 
President Joseph Ejercito Estrada. As one of the Senator-Judges, the public 
marveled at Senator Enrile\'s admirable display of legal expertise. As a lawyer 
who has not lost a single case when he practiced law after passing the bar with 
a perfect score in Commercial Law, he dutifully performed the gargantuan task of 
rendering impartial justice during the impeachment trial. His strong 
determination to uphold the Constitution earned him the sternest of rebuke from 
some sectors that misunderstood the sincerity of his stand. <BR><BR>Every inch a 
seasoned statesman, Senator Enrile managed to regain the confidence of the 
people when they realized the candor and honesty of his intentions. In the 
recent SWS Survey, he landed in the magic 12, a feat that was elusive even to 
those who figured prominently during the impeachment trial by joining the 
bandwagon. <BR><BR>This coming election, the public will again bear witness to 
an active demonstration of how democracy operates in the country by putting in 
power to only those candidates with proven competence, integrity and genuine 
desire to serve the Filipino people. One such man is SENATOR JUAN PONCE ENRILE, 
who stood up not only like a man, but also as an honorable statesman. <BR>', '', '', '', '[Source: <A HREF=\"http://www.juanponceenrile.com/profile-english.html\">http://www.juanponceenrile.com/profile-english.html</A>]<BR><BR>
<P>
One such man grew up poor and out of wedlock and continues to influence world 
events. His EDSA led revolt became a model for toppling repressive regimes all 
over the world. <BR><BR>Juan Ponce Enrile was born on Valentine\'s Day in a 
remote village in Cagayan. He was christened Juanito Furagganan, taking his 
mother\'s name. <BR><BR>Looking for better opportunities, the young Juanito left 
Gonzaga, Cagayan for the poblacion and enrolled in school by working as a 
servant to his mother\'s relative. <BR><BR>He later transferred to Aparri and 
enrolled at the Cagayan Valley Institute. <BR><BR>World War II broke out and 
Juanito, now a young man joined the guerillas. He was caught, imprisoned and 
tortured. He escaped, and at the end of the war, was serving in the U.S. 
Quartermaster depot in Aparri, Cagayan. <BR><BR>While the war was raging, his 
half sisters evacuated to Aparri and learned about Juanito. <BR><BR>After the 
war, Juanito met his father in the latter\'s Law Office in Binondo, Manila. 
<BR><BR>Don Alfonso brought Juanito home to Malabon. He was given a new name, 
Juan Ponce Enrile. He resumed his High School education at the St. James Academy 
in Malabon. <BR><BR>In 1947, he entered Ateneo de Manila graduating cum laude 
with an Associate in Arts Degree. In the UP, he graduated cum laude and 
salutatorian of UP Law Class 1953. He later passed the Bar Examinations placing 
11th with a 91.72% rating and getting a perfect score in commercial law. 
<BR><BR>He was offered a scholarship by the Harvard University where he earned a 
Master of Laws degree specializing in taxation and corporate reorganization. 
<BR><BR>Returning to the Philippines, he joined the Ponce Enrile, Siguion Reyna, 
Montecillo, Bello Law Office where he emerged as a top corporate and litigation 
lawyer. He never lost a case. <BR><BR>In 1966, he was appointed as 
Undersecretary of Finance, acting Insurance Commissioner of Customs and acting 
Chairman of the Monetary Board. In 1968-70 he served as Secretary of Justice. He 
was appointed Secretary of National Defense in 1970, a position he held for 
almost seventeen (17) years until 1986. <BR><BR>He became an Assemblyman of 
Cagayan in 1978 and was reelected in 1984. <BR><BR>The events of February 1986 
marked turning point in the history of the Philippines and in Enrile\'s career. 
Following the turbulent snap elections of February 7,1986, and amid the 
prolonged crisis that gripped the country after the assassination of former 
Senator Benigno Aquino, Jr., Enrile withdrew his support for the Marcos 
government and led the revolt that triggered what would be known as the People 
Power or EDSA Revolution. <BR><BR>Together with a handful of officers and men, 
he rallied the ranks of the Philippine military behind the rebellion, which 
culminated in the fall of the Marcos government. <BR><BR>It was during this time 
that hundreds of thousands of citizens poured into EDSA (Epifanio Delos Santos 
Avenue) and for four days surrounded the camp where Enrile and his men were 
holding out, thus averting a bloody confrontation between the rebels and Marcos 
loyalist group in the military. <BR><BR>Mrs. Corazon Aquino, who was proclaimed 
the New President, reappointed Enrile as Secretary of National Defense. He the 
post after six months, however, as differences over policy with the new 
administration grew. <BR><BR>In 1987, he ran and won as opposition Senator. 
Subsequently, was the lone opposition Senator in the Senate. As Minority Floor 
Leader, he was a member of all the standing committees of the Senate. He was 
also a member of the Senate Electoral Tribunal and the Commission on 
Appointments. <BR><BR>In the May 11, 1992 elections, he won a seat in the House 
of Representatives by a landslide representing the First District of Cagayan, 
his home province. He joined the Liberal Party, to which his father belonged, 
shortly after. <BR><BR>In the May 1995 elections he ran and won a seat once 
again in the Senate under the Lakas Coalition. Again he was a member of the 
Commission on Appointments and Chairman of the Senate Ways and Means Committee 
and the Committee on Government Corporations and Public Enterprises. <BR><BR>At 
that time, he authored the Comprehensive Tax Reform Program, which eventually 
became Republic Act 8424. Among the inclusions that would greatly benefit the 
Overseas Filipino Worker in this law is the exemption of their income earned 
abroad from taxation, thus enabling them to save a more substantial amount from 
their salaries for their families. In addition to this, is the exemption from 
capital gains tax, proceeds realized from the sale of one\'s family home provided 
that such gains would be utilized to acquire another residential home. 
<BR><BR>During the 10th and 11th Congress, Senator Juan Ponce Enrile filed 
several legislative landmarks namely: the; SB No. 2068 which seeks to increase 
by at least 100% the personal and additional tax exemptions granted to 
individual income tax payers; SB. No. 2089 which seeks to reduce the income tax 
rates on taxable income; SB 1887 which would allow the deductibility from 
taxable income of interest payments on housing loans, and in addition, SB No. 
2082 which seeks to exempt all the allowances and benefits granted to public 
school teachers, including those in state colleges and universities from income 
tax. <BR><BR>He has gone on to serve as one of the most productive and 
outstanding senators in the present Congress. <BR><BR>He has continued to serve 
as he has lived- with excellence, determination and desire to serve the Filipino 
people. <BR>', 'Gonzaga, Cagayan', '', '', '', '2', '20010623104303', '', '[Source: <A HREF=\"http://www.juanponceenrile.com/legislative-agenda.html\">http://www.juanponceenrile.com/legislative-agenda.html</A>]<BR><BR>
<P>
I consider the following as the top priorities for the nation included in my 
legislative agenda as Senator of the Philippines should I be fortunate enough to 
be re-elected as Senator this coming elections: <BR><BR><B>THE ECONOMY</B> 
<HR width=\"100%\" SIZE=1>
We have to calibrate carefully the exchange rate so that we neither price 
ourselves out of the world market nor allow the peso to depreciate. An 
acceptable exchange rate must be determined in relation to our neighbors and our 
competitors. With respect to interest rates, I advocate the policy of fostering 
competition - not regulation - to bring down interest rate levels. I will 
directly compete with the commercial banks by providing credit lower rates. 
<BR><BR>I have long ago taken the position that we must reduce the tax burden on 
the people. Primarily, I am advocating this as a creative way of increasing the 
free or disposable income of taxpayers and spurring economic activity. 
<BR><BR>We must realize that no matter how much we press for salary increases, 
employers are hardly in a position, especially given the economic situation, to 
give their employees the substantial wage increase they need to cope with the 
rise in cost of living. A cut in taxes will automatically increase the take home 
pay of our salaried employees and thus enable them to buy more goods. The 
economy will benefit in turn from increased spending and economic activity. 
<BR><BR>During the last Congress, I filed two related bills aimed at achieving 
this goal to wit, Senate Bill No. 2068 which seeks to increase the allowable 
personal and addition exemptions of individual taxpayers by at least 100%; and 
Senate Bill No. 2089 aimed at reducing the corresponding tax rates of individual 
taxpayers by at least 50%. Public hearings for the passage of this bill were 
held and the corresponding Committee Reports were prepared. I even went to the 
extent of sponsoring it in the Senate before we adjourned. <BR><BR>Moreover, to 
further protect the consuming public from the predatory practices of some 
unscrupulous businessmen, I will pursue the enactment of an Anti-Trust Law that 
will check and penalize any act or practice that will in one way or the other 
result in any combination or monopoly in restraint of trade. <BR><BR>If 
re-elected, I vow to pursue these and other measures aimed at reducing the tax 
burden on the people so that they can have more money in their hands for their 
basic needs. <BR><BR><B>PEACE AND ORDER</B> 
<HR width=\"100%\" SIZE=1>
I advocate the return of jurisdiction and control over the police to the local 
governments. Nationalizing the police has only turned the law enforcement effort 
into a bureaucratic mess. We should maintain a national constabulary at a 
national level to attend to peace and order problems that are national in 
nature. <BR><BR><B>GOVERNMENT REORGANIZATION</B> 
<HR width=\"100%\" SIZE=1>
I advocate the following: 
<UL>
<LI>Adoption of the generalized civil service system of the British Civil 
Service, in lieu of our present compartmentalized system. Under that system, a 
civil servant is considered as an employee of the entire government service not 
of specific departments or agencies. Thus, he or she can be easily moved from 
one department to another. 
<LI>Review of the entire government bureau so as to remove duplication of 
agencies and services to make the government not only less wasteful but more 
efficient as well. 
<LI>Restoration of the full powers of the Commission on Appointments of Congress 
under which all officials of the bureaucracy down to assistant director level 
must pass the scrutiny of the Commission. This will help arrest profusion of 
political appointments to the civil service. 
<LI>Abolition of the Judicial and Bar Council, which at present recommends to 
the President appointments to the courts. </LI></UL><B>EDUCATION</B> 
<HR width=\"100%\" SIZE=1>
To achieve high-quality education, we should focus attention on the three areas 
where reform can result in positive change for our society: 
<UL>
<LI>The quality of teachers and teacher training; 
<LI>The physical facilities of our institutions of learning; and 
<LI>The substance of the curriculum. </LI></UL>During the past Congress, I filed 
several Senate Bills that will boost our education system into the new 
millennium. An example of which concentrates on information technology (IT) 
education since the IT industry is the wave of the future. Another bill proposes 
to exempt the allowances granted to public school teachers from taxation to 
entice more people to join the academe. <BR><BR>We must also create more State 
Colleges and Universities so that more Filipino students may be given the 
opportunity to enroll at a low cost. <BR><BR>If re-elected, I shall continue to 
pursue my vision for Education by re-filing these bills, file other related 
measures and work on the passage of the same. <BR><BR><B>NATIONAL SECURITY</B> 
<HR width=\"100%\" SIZE=1>
I wholly support the modernization of our armed forces. What we need are modern 
weapon systems. Because we do not have all the available resources for full AFP 
modernization, we should set priorities. Between the Navy and the Air Force, I 
believe we should pour resources into the Navy because we are an archipelagic 
nation. <BR><BR><B>FOREIGN RELATIONS</B> 
<HR width=\"100%\" SIZE=1>
We should nurture our membership in ASEAN and other Asian forums; APEC and our 
relations with countries like the United States of America, Canada, Australia 
and Latin America. Our ties with Europe and the Middle East are of vital 
importance as well particularly in terms of trade and investment. We must strive 
to contribute our share to the work of the United Nations, of which the 
Philippines is a founding member. <BR><BR><B>CONSTITUTIONAL REFORM</B> 
<HR width=\"100%\" SIZE=1>
I believe we should face, once and for all, the challenge of amending our 
Constitution. Among the reforms that I consider urgent are the following: 
<UL>
<LI>The desynchronization of elections; 
<LI>The election of senators by regions; 
<LI>The review of the terms of office of all elective officials of the 
government; 
<LI>The return of supervision and control of the police to the local 
governments; 
<LI>The restoration of the full powers of the Commission on Appointments to 
review presidential appointments; 
<LI>The transfer of court supervision from the Supreme Court to the Department 
of Justice as provided for in the 1935 Constitution; 
<LI>The creation of a two-party system; and 
<LI>The re-examination of the constitutional provisions governing the economy 
and private ownership. </LI></UL>', 'JPE', '', '9606265', '2', '7212000', 'N', '584571', '541913', '1225322', '1745658', '335930', '481004', '362370', '420994', '312857', '407278', '805869', '363607', '176882', '78563', '1527879', '235247', '321', '');
INSERT INTO candsenators VALUES ( '11', 'Ejercito Estrada', 'Luisa Ejercito', 'P', '465', 'candsenator - loi ejercito.jpg', '1930-06-02', '', '', '<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>Being a doctor of medicine 
herself, Dr. Loi Ejercito Estrada has put health on th top shelf of her program 
for the people. She relies on the statistics that thousands if not a million of 
the poor especially live and die without seeing a doctor. So the solution is 
more clinics and hospitals, desirably one for each town with the doctors and 
nurses and personnel subsidized by more taxes. And no one should be denied 
assistance or should be banned and even kept imprisoned in a hospital if he 
cannot pay for such service.<BR><BR>This goes in tandem with a huge program for 
education where the poor are given enough chances to move up to a better life. 
There should be more scholarships offered and they should put a complete stop to 
\"colorum\" schools. There should be more schools, but these should be keenly 
supervised. There must be more teachers even if we have to pay them topnotch 
salaries. Only then can we hope for the children to grow up to our 
targets.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>Labor is needing much 
improvement. More jobs should be generated and that means more companies should 
be encouraged in putting up shop and employ as many as they can pay decently. 
But we must be exceedingly sure that the businesses don\'t fold up because of 
unreasonable demands of labor, such as sky-high wages. We must make sure too 
that proper taxes are paid, both by employers and employed to keep the 
government on a steady keel. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>Security is not too much of 
a problem if it is only a danger of outside interference we are looking at. The 
problem is within us, among us and because of us. We are still in a state of 
rebellion from the communists and the Muslim brothers. They have to be educated 
to join the civil society and not mess around with us. While the police and 
military should always maintain a close watch, the civil government and civilian 
institutions can do a lot to alleviate their grievances and poor station in 
life.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>This is the root of the 
problem of poverty - Lack of work, especially quality work that can sustain the 
lives of people all around. This demands their employment and education to 
uplift themselves. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>There are too many of us 
still living in hovels and eating only twice a day and only ride wiith, 
probably, a little \"bagoong.\" There must be a remedy to that and the remedy is 
work and education.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>When all is said and done, 
we have to go back to one who said laws must be fashioned out more for the poor 
that fore the rich. <BR></FONT></P>', '', '', '', 'Iba, Zambales', '', '', '', '2', '20010623104303', '', '', 'Loi', '', '10456674', '2', '7834231', 'Y', '579134', '419406', '1457043', '1994034', '389919', '503943', '320503', '467106', '362112', '472652', '903578', '426055', '159356', '102585', '1649317', '249701', '230', '');
INSERT INTO candsenators VALUES ( '12', 'Flavier', 'Juan', 'M', '233', 'candsenator - juan flavier.jpg', '1935-06-23', '', '', '', '', '', '[Source: <A HREF=\"http://ebantay.free3.org/candidate.php3?c=9\">http://ebantay.free3.org/candidate.php3?c=9</A>]<BR><BR>
<P>
Dr. Flavier is a Senator of the Republic of the Philippines. He is Chairman of the Social Justice, Welfare and Development Committee of the Senate. He also sat on the Cultural Communities Committee and the Science and Technology Committee. 
<P>
From 1992 until 1995, he was a Cabinet Member, serving as Secretary of Health. In 1977, he served as President of the Philippine Rural Reconstruction Movement. He was also President of the International Institute of Rural Reconstruction from 1978 until 1992. Dr. Flavier received his medical credentials from the University of the Philippines in 1960. He received a Masters in Public Health from Johns Hopkins University in 1969.', 'Tondo, Manila', '', '', '', '2', '20010623104303', '', '', 'Johnny F.', '', '11676129', '1', '8877404', 'Y', '838110', '350680', '1519409', '1714051', '609255', '1018434', '1045536', '446363', '294422', '317140', '591372', '182635', '260764', '168824', '2037629', '281205', '300', '');
INSERT INTO candsenators VALUES ( '13', 'Herrera', 'Ernesto', 'F', '233', 'candsenator - ernesto herrera.jpg', '1942-09-11', '', '', '', '', '', '[Source: <A HREF=\"http://ebantay.free3.org/candidate.php3?c=23\">http://ebantay.free3.org/candidate.php3?c=23</A>]<BR><BR>
<FONT face=\"helvetica, arial\" size=2>
<P>Former Senator Ernesto \"Boy\" Herrera earned for himself an enviable 
reputation as a trade union leader, an advocate of law and order, a crusader 
against drug abuse, an expert on public finance an done of the outstanding 
senators of the 8th, 9th and 10th Congresses. 
<P>He earned his LI.B from the University of the Visayas in 1966. In 1995, he 
took his Masters Degree (summa cum laude) in Public Administration, major in 
Public Finance, at the Lyceum of the Philippines, where he also obtained his 
Ph.D (magna cum laude) in Fiscal Studies in 1998. The thesis for his M.A. was a 
comparative analysis of the tax systems of the ASEAN countries and Hong Kong. 
His Ph.D. dissertation was o the issues and problems of legislative control of 
the national budget. He was cconferred honorary doctorates in humanities by the 
University of the Visayas in 1994 and by the University of Bohol in 1998. 
<P>Boy Herrera spent most of his professional life in the cause of labor, mainly 
as General Secretary of the Trade Union Congress of the Philippines. 
<P>He was the only Filipino member of the Executive Board of the International 
Confederation of Free Trade Unions iin Brussels, Belgium, from 1988 - 1992; a 
consultant on employment and workers\' education of the International Labour 
Organisation (ILO) in Geneva, Switzerland. He headed the Workers\' Delegation to 
the 75th Session of the ILO where he delivered a major address on human rights. 
<P>He is the first Asian, and only the second individual, to recieve the George 
Meanly International Human Rights Award in 1985. The first individual awardee 
was Lech Walesa of the Solidarity Movement, former President of Poland. He was 
likewise conferred the International Award of Honor by the International 
Narcotics Enforcement Officers Association in New York, U.S.A., in 1991. 
<P>Here at home, Boy Herrera was the workers\' representative in the National 
Wages Council, the Social Security Commission and the National Manpower and 
Youth Council. He is the Founding Chairman of teh Citizens\' DrugWatch 
Foundation, Inc. and President of both the Carlos P. Garcia Foundatin, Inc. and 
the University of the Visayas Alumni Association. In recognition of his crusade 
against drugs particularly to protect the youth from its perricious effects, 
Herrera received the 1992 Gintong Ama ng Bayan Award, the highest award given by 
the Gintong Ama/Ina Foundation of the Philippines. 
<P>Boy Herrera rose to national prominence as a member of the Agrava 
Fact-Finding Board that investigated the assassination of Benigno S. Aquino Jr. 
<P>Herrera was first elected to the Senate in 1987. In the national elections of 
1992, he won his seecond Senate term, ranking second among the re-electionist 
senators. In the Senate, he chaired the Committees on Ways and Means, Finance, 
Public Services, Labor, Tourism and Illegal Drugs. He wa a member of the 
Commission of Appointments, chairman of its committee on Constitutional Offices. 

<P>He was a member of the Congressional Commissions on Education (Edcom, 1990) 
that reviewed and assessed the Philippine educational system and on Health 
(1992). In the Edcom, he was responsible for landmark reforms in vocational 
education and training that resulted in the establishment of the Technical 
Educational and Skills Development Authority (TESDA). He also sat on the 
Executive-Legislative National Water Crisis Commission. He was a member of the 
Congressional Commission on Health and was responsible for the Philippine Health 
Insurance System. 
<P>In the Senate, his legislative record was strong on labor, employment, 
fiscal, education and law and order policies, and was its leading advocate in 
the control and prevention of drug abuse. 
<P>In the Commission on Appointment, he chaired the committees on Accounts, 
Constitutional Bodies and Sciece &amp; Technology. He is also a member of the 
Congressional Commission on Labor. 
<P>He has 34 laws to his credit, one of the highest achivements in the 8th, 9th, 
10th and the on-going, 11th, Congresses. 
<P>Herrera was one of the three complainants that became the basis of the 
Articles of Impeachment against Joseph E. Estrada. He was a moving force of the 
Power Power II. 
<P>Born in Samboan, Cebu, on September 11, 1942, he is married to Lourdes Cuico 
of Cebu City and has four children: Luzil, June, Ernesto II and Ernesto III. 
Ernesto F. Herrera, like Apolinario Mabini, overcame his physical handicap 
(cause by polio during his childhood) to become one of the country\'s outstanding 
learders. 
<P>Making a crippled country whole again 
<P><I>Ako po\'y si Boy Herrera - tubong Cebu - anak ng isang sundalo. Ang aking 
nanay ay Boholana. 
<P>Di man n\'yo naitatanong - ako\'y nagkasakit ng polio noong ako\'y apat na taong 
gulang lamang. 
<P>Sa kabila ng aming kahirapan at nang aking kapansanan - ako po\'y nakatapos ng 
abogasya sa University of the Visayas. 
<P>Matapos akong magturo sumandali, ako\'y naging organizer ng mga estibidor sa 
Cebu at ng mga trabahador sa malaking pataniman sa Mindanao. 
<P>Nilibot ko ang mga asyendang pinya ng Dole at Del Monte - kadalasan angkas sa 
motorsiklo - at (kung minamalas naman) sa bubong ng jeepney. 
<P>Ako ang isa sa mga nagtatag ng TUCP at ako ay naging Secretary General nito. 
<P></I>Then Senator Benigno Aquino was assassinated - and I became a member of 
the Agrava Fact-Finding Board. Only then did I realize how much harm an 
oppressive Government can do to a nation and its people. 
<P><I>Kung walang pangitain - walang kakayahan - at walang moralidad ang mga 
nasa poder, sila\'y nagsisilbing hagupit sa taong-bayan. 
<P>Nilabanan ko ang nais ni Maros na pawalang sala ang mga sundalong pumaslang 
kay Ninoy. Ito ang nagbunsod ng EDSA I. 
<P>Ako\'y hinirang ni Presidente Cory upang kumandidato para sa Senado noong 
1987. 
<P></I>During my first term, I realized that being a Senator required advanced 
and continuing education. So, without neglecting my duties as Senator, I went to 
night school. I took my master\'s degree in public finance graduating summa cum 
laude. I enrolled for a doctorate in fiscal studies, graduating magna cum laude. 

<P>During my two terms as Senator - from 1987 until 1999 - I authored 34 
landmark laws. I wrote the TESDA Law to prepare young people for jobs. I wrote 
the Migrant Workers Act to protect OFWs. I wrote the Death Penalty Law to stop 
heinous crimes. 
<P>I passed the Paternity Leave Act to strengthen the family. A strong family, 
as a I found early in life, is an indispensable support to a strong nation. And 
i founded the Citizens\' DrugWatch to fight drug addiction. My other laws are on 
monetary and fiscal policies and on public health. 
<P>Laws I now would like to write - if i am reelected to the Senate - are those 
that will create jobs and ensure that our society is free of corruption. 
<P><I>Napakarami sa ating mga Pilipino ang nilulumpo ng karalitaan at 
kamangmangan. Mistulang mga pipi ang ating mga manggagawa - sapagkat di nila 
maipaabot sa mga nasa kapangyarihan ang kanilang mga inaasam-asam. At napakarami 
sa ating mga pinuno - bulag na sa salapi - ay bingi pa rin sa himutok ng 
kanilang mga nasasakop. 
<P></I>These past three years, ang buong bansa natin ay nasalanta ng katiwalian. 
Like the polio virus, corruption entered the nation\'s bloodstream - and if left 
unchecked, maaring masalanta ang buong bansa. 
<P>This was why I joined Heherson Alvarez and Mike Defensor in making the 
accusations na naging basihan ng mga Articles of Impeachment against President 
Estrada. 
<P>EDSA II launched this People Power Coalition with a clear purpose. 
<P>Never again should we put in power the minions of a corrupt administration. 
<P>Never again should we stand by and watch powerful people prevent Filipinos 
from walking tall and proud in the global community. 
<P>This - my beloved countrymen - is the parable of my life that I offer to you. 
Together, let us do great things for our country and our people.</P></FONT>', 'Samboan, Cebu', '', '', '', '2', '20010623104303', '', '', 'Boy', '', '6743297', '1', '5186007', 'N', '387174', '144829', '786496', '782383', '295629', '603158', '941044', '325101', '281213', '273348', '360742', '126778', '107682', '130510', '997809', '199259', '142', '');
INSERT INTO candsenators VALUES ( '14', 'Honasan', 'Gregorio', 'B', '465', 'candsenator - gringo honasan.jpg', '1948-03-14', '', '', '<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>The legislative agenda of 
Senator Honasan for the 11th Congress revolves around Good Government and 
Efficient Bureaucracy; Reforms in AFP and PNP; Industrialization and Genuine 
Economic Development; Natural Resources and Environmental Protection and 
Management; Good Education for all and Opportunities for the Marginalized 
Sectors. His legislative priorities include:</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B>The Land Use Act (Senate 
Bill No. 660)</B> - an act providing for the national land use policy and 
planning network expected to provide a systematic zoning of land resources for 
industrial, economic, agricultural and community use.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B>Clean Water Act (Senate 
Bill 1710)</B> - an act providing for a comprehensive water resource policy and 
water sector development, creating the Water Resources Management commission and 
for other purposes;</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B>An Act Declaring a 
National Peace Policy (Senate Bill 660) </B>- creating the Commission on Peace 
and provide the guideline for government\'s dealings with rebels, insurgents and 
secessionist groups; </FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B>Reorganization Act of the 
DAR (Senate Bill 1589)</B> - includes the creation of the Department of Agrarian 
Reform Adjudication Board or DARAB; and</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B>Magna Carta for PNP 
(Senate Bill no. 1918)</B> - seen as the answer to the woes of policemen over 
low pay, \"palakasan system,\" security of tenure, financial assistance and 
benefits, logistical problems and training</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B>Amending the AFP 
Retirement Law (Senate Bill 1312)</B> - The bill seeks to correct the injustice 
committed against men in uniform over the computation of their retirement 
benefits</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>Full Implementation of 
Indigenous People\'s Right Act or IPRA - to give cultural minorities due 
protection </FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B>PERA for Government 
Workers (Senate Bill 1444)</B> - provides a P1,000 Personal Economic Relief 
Assistance (PERA) to government workers <BR></FONT></P>', '', '', '', 'Baguio City', '', '', '', '2', '20010623104303', '', '', 'Gringo', '', '10364272', '2', '7750473', 'Y', '639176', '463880', '1315176', '1944118', '463297', '509241', '342821', '486104', '362443', '445179', '879460', '414274', '185526', '86999', '1594942', '231298', '338', '');
INSERT INTO candsenators VALUES ( '15', 'Lacson', 'Panfilo', 'M', '243', 'candsenator - ping lacson.jpg', '1948-06-01', '', '', '[Source: <A HREF=\"http://www.pinglacson.net/ping_lacson_ie/platform.htm\">http://www.pinglacson.net/ping_lacson_ie/platform.htm</A>]<BR><BR>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B>1.) PEACE AND 
ORDER</B></FONT></P>
<P><B><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>2.) ANTI-GRAFT 
AND CORRUPTION</FONT></B></P>
<P><B><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>3.) GOOD 
GOVERNANCE</FONT></B></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>\"MISSION POSSIBLE\" 
SA SENADO</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>UPANG SUGPUIN ANG 
KRIMEN AT KURAKOT</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>1.) Magtatag ng 
isang \"Independent Commision Against Corruption\" na hindi saklaw ninuman. Maski 
ng Pangulo ng Pilipinas upang makasigurong anumang imbestigasyon nito laban sa 
katiwalian ay di maimpluwensiyahan ninuman.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>2.) Magsabatas ng 
isang sistema nang pagmomonitor ng pananalapi para masugpo ang \"Unexplained 
Wealth.\"</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>3.) Palakasin pa 
ang mga batas laban sa mga sindikato ng krimen, lalong-lalo na sa droga, 
kidnap-for-ransom at iba pang malaking krimen.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>4.) Maiangat ang 
kabuhayan ng ating kapulisan at militar upang higit silang maging epektibo sa 
kanilang panunungkulan.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>PROTEKSIYON SA 
MAMIMILI AT MALILIIT NA MAGANGALAKAL</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>1.) Palakasin ang 
Consumer Code upang bigyang proteksiyon ang mamimili laban sa masama at 
mapang-abusong serbisyo ng ng mga public utility vehicles tulad ng mga cellphone 
companies, bulok na mga barko, transportasyon atbp.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>2.) Itaguyod ang 
kapayakan ng mga maliliit na negosyante laban sa sobrang buwis at mapaniil na 
regulasyon.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>3.) Gawing simple 
at taxpayer-friendly ang sistema ng buwis, upang maiwasan ang kurakot at 
madagdagan ang kita ng pamahalaan.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>4.) Maitaguyod ang 
pagkakaroon ng small at medium enterprises upang magkaroon ng dagdag na 
ikabubuhay ng mga ordinaryo nating mamamayan at maiangat aang kanilang 
kabuhayan.</FONT></P>', '', '', '[Source: <A HREF=\"http://www.pinglacson.net/ping_netscape/profile_content.htm\">http://www.pinglacson.net/ping_netscape/profile_content.htm</A>]<BR><BR>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" color=#666666 size=2>With 
Lacson again in anti-crime mode, kidnappings and bank robberies have dropped 
dramatically. Also, he has retrieved some 448 carnapped or missing vehicles 
being used by police officers; relieved from duty 42 police officers, including 
four generals and two colonels, who headed major Manila police commands; banned 
officers from playing golf during office hours at the PNP\'s sprawling Camp Crame 
headquarters in suburban Quezon City; and stopped the police checkpoints on 
delivery vans bringing vegetables, fish and other supplies to Manila from the 
provinces. These unpopular checkpoints tend to jack up the price of prime goods 
in the capital because businessmen pass on the cost of extortion money to 
consumers.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" color=#333333 
size=2>Lacson has fielded plainclothes cops to monitor the activities of 
extorting policemen.To hardened scalawags in uniform, Lacson vows, in rather 
dramatic language:</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" color=#666666 
size=2>Policemen are now suddenly courteous. Bad cops have turned good. 
</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" color=#666666 size=2>Not 
surprisingly, a lot of rank-and-file police don\'t like Lacson. \"The moment I 
accepted the command,\" he says, \"I knew my life would become miserable. I would 
lose a lot of friends even as I created new enemies. Those I fight, I do not 
hate. Those I protect, I do not love. It is simply a matter of duty.\" Even if 
not everyone agrees how that duty should be discharged. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" color=#666666 
size=2>Before assuming the top PNP post, Lacson served as chief of the PAOCTF. 
Lacson joined the now defunct Philippine Constabulary upon graduation from the 
Philippine Military Academy in 1971.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" color=#666666 size=2>He 
served most of his junior years with the Metrocom Intelligence and Security 
Group (MISG) from 1971 to 1976. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" color=#666666 size=2>At 
the height of the communist insurgency in Northern Luzon, he was PC/INP 
Provincial Commander of Isabela from 1988 to 1989 after which he was reassigned 
as commander of the Cebu Metrodiscom until 1992.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" color=#666666 size=2>His 
next assignment brought him back to Luzon as provincial director of Laguna in 
1992. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" color=#666666 
size=2>Lacson\'s colorful career as crimebuster peaked when he was appointed 
chief of the Presidential Anti-Crime Commission (PACC}.</FONT></P>', 'Imus, Cavite', '', '', '', '2', '20010623104303', '', '', 'Ping Lacson', '', '10481755', '2', '7867813', 'Y', '608116', '453102', '1387489', '1982636', '408649', '477372', '418210', '462699', '342964', '415952', '886599', '411419', '181820', '76610', '1713864', '253986', '268', '');
INSERT INTO candsenators VALUES ( '16', 'Lozano', 'Oliver', 'O', '249', 'candsenator - oliver lozano.jpg', '1940-05-13', '', '', '<FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>1. Work for the release of $ 
647 million Marcos deposit with PNB to be shared with the entire Filipino people 
regardless of religious and political beliefs in accordance with the last will 
of President Ferdinand E. Marcos. Hindi pera bawat isa, kundi pondo bawat 
proyekto. (Release is entry point for global recovery of multi-million Marcos 
dollar and gold deposits for the benefit of the people.) </FONT>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>2. Fair regulation of 
tuition fees, gasoline prices, water rates and electric rates thru due process 
and after full and fair hearing to avoid arbitrary fees and rates.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>3. Fair increase of salaries 
of teachers, soldiers, policemen, workers and public employees after 
consultation without dismissal. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>4. Fair increase of 
veterans\' pension not lower than P 5,000/mo.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>5. Low - cost housing for 
media practitioners, soldiers, policemen, teachers, workers, government 
employees, veterans and Overseas Filipino Workers (OFW\'s).</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>6. Appropriate place of 
worship for different religious groups. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>7. Fair and honorable peace 
accord with and rehabilitation of our Muslim brothers coupled with economic 
development.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>8. Relocation and 
rehabilitation of squatters, street children, and victims of women/child abuse 
upang may \"bahay at hanapbuhay\".</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>9. Recreational and 
Rehabilitation Center for Senior Citizens with complete facilities.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>10. Strengthen the sports 
program for youth and national athletes.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>11. Even playing fields for 
investors: No cronyism. No behest loans. </FONT></P>
<P align=center><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B>¨ IN ALL THE 
ABOVEMENTIONED SUBJECTS/PROBLEMS, I HUMBLY SUBMIT MY IMMEDIATE SOLUTION; 
</B><BR><BR>THAT IS - THE USE OF THE $647 MILLION MARCOS DEPOSIT WITH THE PNB 
(Philippine National Bank) UPON RELEASE FOR THE BENEFIT OF THE FILIPINO PEOPLE 
REGARDLESS OF RELIGIOUS OR POLITICAL BELIEFS. LEGISLATION ALONE CANNOT SOLVE THE 
ECONOMIC CRISIS. </FONT></P>', '', '', '', 'Dingras Ilocos Norte', '', '', '', '2', '20010623104303', '', '', 'Oli', '', '467571', '0', '403151', 'N', '44701', '12387', '59055', '67240', '9515', '12242', '14215', '17427', '8135', '8577', '22424', '9599', '11185', '5164', '158559', '7132', '14', '');
INSERT INTO candsenators VALUES ( '17', 'Madrigal', 'Ma. Ana', 'C', '243', 'candsenator - jamby madrigal.jpg', '1958-04-26', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'Manila', '', '', '', '1', '20010623104303', '', '<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><I><B>A. GENERAL 
ISSUES</B></I></FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>POVERTY. Need to empower 
children , enrich their lives through Christian values.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>POPULATION. Responsible 
parenthood, with the precepts of Christian values.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>GRAFT AND CORRUPTION. Start 
by example. Need for young blood.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>ENVIRONMENT AND NATURAL 
RESOURCES. Sustainable development. Residents should be encouraged to help 
manage their own environment.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>CRIME PREVENTION. Prevention 
of violence at home.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>TERRORISM. All-out war in 
Mindanao.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>ARTS AND CULTURE. 
Preservation of Arts and culture for the youth. Amenable to the establishment of 
a separate Department of Arts and Culture.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>HOUSING. Sustainable 
housing, with access to schools, markets, clinics, etc. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY. The 
Philippines can be competitive.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>REVENUE COLLECTION. Let the 
rich pay their taxes.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>JUSTICE SYSTEM. Empowerment 
of the poor before they can have justice.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>ABOLITION OF ROTC. There is 
need for discipline.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>SCIENCE AND TECHNOLOGY. 
Promotion of and support to science and technology. Provide incentives and give 
due recognition to Filipinos who excel in science and technology.</FONT></P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B><I>B. POLITICAL 
ISSUES</I></B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>GOOD GOVERNANCE. Welfare of 
the majority before anything else. Consultation with the people regarding issues 
that affect all. Encourage transparency in decision making and 
governance.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>CONSTITUTIONAL REFORMS. 
Build a stable nation first.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>SEPARATION OF CHURCH AND 
STATE. Church should empower the poor.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>PEACE NEGOTIATIONS. Peaceful 
society towards a developed society. Open our corridors for peace but let us not 
compromise our sovereignty.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>FORM OF GOVERNMENT. Need to 
strengthen the Presidential system by constitutional means.</FONT></P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B><I>C. BUSINESS AND 
ECONOMY</I></B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>ECONOMIC REFORMS. Narrow the 
gap between the rich and poor. More equitable distribution of wealth.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>OIL DEREGULATION. Fact is, 
RP has cheaper oil than other countries.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>PRIVATIZATION. Should be 
selective.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>GLOBALIZATION. Need for 
safety nets.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>GATT/WTO. Need for safety 
nets; without them, our agriculture will suffer.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>REFORMS IN THE BANKING 
SYSTEM. Should proceed slowly, otherwise, there might be capital 
flight.</FONT></P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B><I>D. MORAL 
ISSUES</I></B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>FAMILY PLANNING. Responsible 
parenthood.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>ABORTION. The unborn child 
has a right to live.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>DEATH PENALTY. Against. We 
need proper reforms in our prisons.</FONT></P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B><I>E. SECTORAL 
ISSUES</I></B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>WOMEN. Encourage active 
participation of women.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>ELDERLY. More 
programs.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>INDIGENOUS PEOPLES. More 
programs.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>DISABLED. Need for major 
programs.</FONT></P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><B><I>F.CHILDRENS 
ISSUES</I></B></FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>EDUCATION. Improvement of 
the quality of education for all, with focus on the modernization of facilities 
and method of teaching. Proper support should be given to all public school 
teachers, to improve the quality of their performance. This would include 
training and other necessary programs.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>HEALTH AND NUTRITION. Need 
for proper information on health and nutrition. A healthy child can think well 
and function properly in school. Healthy population towards a developed society 
through proper nutrition and health practices. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>CHILD LABOR AND 
EXPLOITATION. Anti-child labor and exploitation. Support for bills opposing 
child labor and exploitation.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>DRUG ADDICTION. All-out war 
against drugs.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>CHILD PROSTITUTION. All-out 
war.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>JUVENILE DELINQUENCY. Reform 
in law on juvenile delinquency.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>ENVIRONMENT. Clean and 
healthy environment for all. Sustainable economic growth compatible with 
environmental protection. Promotion of greater responsibility for local 
communities over their environments, including them in decision making and 
management of their resources. Educating people on the importance of sustainable 
development and environment protection.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2>CHILD FRIENDLY SOCIETY. 
Promotion of the rights of every child. More active participation of children in 
the society. Creation of an environment for children where they can develop 
their potential and become responsible citizens of society.</FONT></P>', 'Jamby Madrigal', '', '5029564', '2', '3760258', 'N', '216371', '137423', '701037', '1079884', '164151', '226163', '131870', '178200', '144429', '183229', '414116', '197824', '55701', '34195', '1061748', '103109', '114', '');
INSERT INTO candsenators VALUES ( '18', 'Magsaysay', 'Ramon Jr.', 'B', '465', 'candsenator - jun magsaysay.jpg', '1938-06-05', '', '', '', '', '', '[Source: <A HREF=\"http://www.magsaysay.com/profile/profile-about.htm\">http://www.magsaysay.com/profile/profile-about.htm</A>]<BR><BR>
<P class=newstitle>Carrying on the Legacy</P>
<P class=newstext>Senator Ramon Magsaysay, Jr. is the only son of the late and 
beloved Philippine President Ramon Magsaysay and Mrs. Luz Banzon-Magsaysay. He 
was born in Manila in 1938. He is married to Marilou Kahn-Magsaysay. His two 
children, Francisco and Margarita, are now both married and with families of 
their own. 
<P class=newstext>His father\'s rise to the presidency in 1953 taught Jun 
Magsaysay and his sisters, Milagros and Teresita, the virtues of integrity, 
honesty and having a strong passion for the welfare of the common man. Inside 
majestic Malacañang the Magsaysays lived humbly, untouched by selfish ambitions 
and unmarred by lust for power. 
<P class=newstitle>An Early Responsibility 
<P class=newstext>With President Magsaysay\'s sudden death in 1957,18-year-old 
Jun inherited greater responsibilities that enabled him to recognize the value 
of perseverance and hard work. He was no longer his father\'s boy. Instantly, he 
had to become the man of the house. 
<P class=newstitle>Education 
<P class=newstext>Jun spent most of his academic years at the De La Salle 
College in Manila where he earned a degree in Mechanical Engineering. He pursued 
his academic studies at Harvard School of Business Administration in Boston, 
Massachusetts and in New York University Graduate School of Business 
Administration. He returned to the Philippines armed with new skills, knowledge, 
and vision that would later become a strong force behind the development of a 
major industry in the country. </P>
<P class=newstitle>Youngest Congressman</P>
<P class=newstext>Being the only son of a revered president, Jun Magsaysay 
carries with him the responsibility of continuing the legacy of championing the 
cause of the common man. Thus in 1966 he was elected as a Congressional 
Representative for the lone district of Zambales. Dubbed as the Benjamin of the 
House of Representatives, he was the youngest Congressman to be elected to the 
Lower House at the age of 27. In Congress, he authored and sponsored bills 
designed to promote the development of science and technology and improve the 
welfare and benefits of private and government workers. Taking after his father, 
Jun bravely declared his positions on issues that affect the conditions of the 
common man.</P>
<P class=newstitle>A Man Who Can Say \'No\'</P>
<P class=newstext>In 1969, he ran for re-election under the opposition Liberal 
Party. Then First Lady Imelda Marcos offered to endorse his candidacy if he will 
leave LP and run under the administration\'s Nacionalista Party. Declining the 
offer, Jun Magsaysay stayed with LP and<BR>was defeated by the powerful NP 
machinery which instead drafted his cousin, Antonio Diaz.</P>
<P class=newstitle>Self-Made Businessman</P>
<P class=newstext>After a productive four-year term in Congress he returned to 
work in the private sector where he ventured into various industries including 
garment manufacturing and export, semi-conductor, and travel and tourism. Armed 
with his business education and engineering skills, Jun pioneered the cable 
television business in the country. Today, with over 550 cable operators 
nationwide, the cable TV industry business has turned into a P2-billion a year 
industry.</P>
<P class=newstitle>Returning to Public Service</P>
<P class=newstext>In 1995, President Ramos invited Jun to join the senatorial 
slate of the Lakas-Laban Coalition as a guest LP candidate. He landed third 
place among the twelve elected senators and first among the neophyte candidates. 
Once again the Filipino people elected a Magsaysay to be one of their leaders in 
government. They trusted the integrity of the son of their beloved President to 
continue the legacy of serving the cause of the common man.</P>
<P class=newstitle>J.O.B.S.</P>
<P class=newstext>In the Senate, Jun Magsaysay worked within the objective of 
providing opportunities that would help improve the living conditions of the 
ordinary Filipino. His program of government is summarized as \'<B>J.O.B.S.</B>\', 
the acronym for Jobs, Opportunities, Business and Security. The laws he helped 
enact were geared toward expanding business and employment opportunities, 
promoting national unity and security.</P>
<P class=newstitle>Quest for Moral Governance</P>
<P class=newstext>On October 12, 2000, five months before he is to embark on a 
re-election bid, Magsaysay resigned from the administration coalition to support 
the people\'s call for the President\'s resignation. His decision to sever ties 
with the administration came in light of clamor for moral governance, with Jun 
Magsaysay believing that the President has &amp;quot;lost his moral authority to 
govern the nation&amp;quot;. Once again, Magsaysay had shown that he is ready to 
turn his back on a powerful machinery that would have ensured his political 
survival, in exchange for a reformed and morally upright government.</P>
<P class=newstitle>Mission to Carry on the Legacy</P>
<P class=newstext>Indeed, President Ramon Magsaysay\'s commitment to the 
Filipinos did not die with him in that tragic plane crash. His son, Jun 
Magsaysay, is living proof that the Filipino people have not entirely lost a 
great leader, he left behind a son to carry on the legacy.</P>', 'Manila', '', '', '', '2', '20010623104303', '', '', 'Jun', '', '11187447', '1', '8505158', 'Y', '766343', '319890', '1422639', '1499971', '599598', '1150881', '1158939', '457435', '313252', '346928', '633670', '197975', '232623', '146493', '1623595', '317044', '171', '');
INSERT INTO candsenators VALUES ( '19', 'Mercado', 'Orlando', 'S', '465', 'candsenator - orly mercado.jpg', '1946-04-26', '', '', '<P><B>S<FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">enator Orly 
Mercado</FONT></B><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"> believes that the 
primary task of a political leader is to ensure that government serves the 
interest of the people, especially the poor. This can only be achieved through 
policies and programs that will:</FONT></P>
<UL>
<LI><B><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">Provide equal opportunity for 
economic activity, education, jobs and livelihood; </FONT></B>
<LI><B><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">improve access to basic 
services such as safe water, housing electricity and health services;</FONT></B> 

<LI><B><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">sustain technology - driven 
reforms in management systems of government to minimize graft and corruption and 
to ensure transparency and accountability;</FONT></B> 
<LI><B><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">conserve environmental 
resources </FONT></B>
<LI><B><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">provide peace, order and 
security </FONT></B></LI></UL>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">These goals cannot be achieved by 
government alone.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">Individuals citizens groups, the 
media, the private sector and the community itself are equally responsible for 
political change and social transformation. These different stakeholders must 
work together not only for economic development but for a just society where the 
poor and other marginalized groups can have more opportunities to improve the 
quality of their lives.</FONT></P>', '', '', '', 'Manila', '', '', '', '2', '20010623104303', '', '', 'Orly', '', '7370087', '2', '5618222', 'N', '397558', '241633', '912014', '1349563', '270137', '402976', '331461', '319010', '228948', '279717', '612245', '306806', '133039', '61538', '1347403', '175814', '225', '');
INSERT INTO candsenators VALUES ( '20', 'Monsod', 'Solita', 'C', '267', 'candsenator - solita monsod.jpg', '1940-07-29', '', '', '', '', '', '[Source: <A HREF=\"http://www.marengwinnie.com/resume-content.htm\">http://www.marengwinnie.com/resume-content.htm</A>]<BR><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P align=center><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><SPAN 
style=\"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica\"><FONT size=3><B><FONT size=2>CURRICULUM 
VITAE</FONT></B></FONT></SPAN></FONT></P>
<P align=center><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" 
size=2><B><SPAN style=\"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica\"><FONT 
face=\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">SOLITAS 
COLLAS-MONSOD</FONT></SPAN></B></FONT></P>
<H1><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><SPAN 
style=\"FONT-FAMILY: Helvetica\"><FONT size=1>PERSONAL 
INFORMATION</FONT></SPAN></FONT></H1></BLOCKQUOTE>
<UL>
<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><FONT size=1>Life 
partner of Christian S. Monsod since June 17, 1961.</FONT></FONT> 
<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Mother to Solita 
Noemi, teacher, director, and stage actress; Toby Melissa, mathematician, 
economist and community organizer; Teresa Patricia, pediatric endocrinologists, 
felloe at Yale Medical Hospital; Christian Enrique, composer, arranger, sound 
engineer and entrepreneur; and Katrina Diane Noelle, senior law student, 
assistant coach of Debating Team and choir director, at Ateneo Law 
School.</FONT> 
<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Sister to Juan G. 
Collas, Anisia Celis, Angela Dean, Diana and Regina.</FONT> 
<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Daughter to Juan 
D. Collas (newspaper, diplomat, author) and</FONT> 
<LI><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Soledad Garduno 
(teacher, social worker, author), both deceased.</FONT> </LI></UL>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H1><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1><B>W O R K E X P E 
R I E N C E</B></FONT></H1>
<H2><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1><B>International 
Experience</B></FONT></H2>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=2><FONT 
size=1>Member, UN Committee for Development Planning (UNCDP), 1987-2000.&nbsp; 
The Committee is a high-level advisory group to the UN-ECOSOC, composed of 24 
experts serving in their personal capacity</FONT></FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Member, Board of 
Trustees, International Food Policy Research Institute (IFPRI) Washington, 
January 1996</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Member, Board of 
Advisors, Human Development Report 1993</FONT><FONT 
face=\"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=1>Member, Board of Advisors, 
South Centre, Geneva, Switzerland, 1991-1995.&nbsp; The South Centre was 
established to follow-up the ecommendations of the South Commission, organized 
